So he loves to drop the F-bomb.

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:15.080
When does he do it?

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:17.279
Well, when he's mad, definitely.

00:01:17.279 --> 00:01:23.839
But really, in every mood if you've seen Ted Lasso, this is his natural mode.

00:01:23.839 --> 00:01:27.879
So we want to look at the number of times he drops F-bombs.

00:01:27.879 --> 00:01:29.559
Now how do I know this?

00:01:29.559 --> 00:01:33.879
Because I watched the episodes at 2x speed and diligently noted them down, including

00:01:33.879 --> 00:01:37.760
the gestures, for science.

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:39.160
So let's dig into the meat of it.

00:01:39.160 --> 00:01:40.160
Let's talk about animation.

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:43.120
But first, I have a question for you.

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:47.040
What season do you think Roy Ken ended up dropping the most number of F-bombs?

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:50.519
And whether you've seen the show or not, I do have a hint for you.

00:01:50.519 --> 00:01:55.279
This is the first episode and how many F-bombs he drops in the very first episode of each

00:01:55.279 --> 00:01:56.279
season.

00:01:56.279 --> 00:01:58.839
So season 1, 2, and 3, it's 2, 11, and 6.

00:01:58.839 --> 00:02:04.839
So if you think it's season 1, raise your hand.

00:02:04.839 --> 00:02:11.800
If you think it's season 2, with the highest count, and if you think it's season 3, raise

00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:12.800
your hand.

00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:19.119
All right, let's find out.

00:02:19.119 --> 00:02:26.119
Let's see by the last quarter if season 2 is going to recover or season 1 going to recover.

00:02:26.119 --> 00:02:30.399
And season 3, you all are winners.

00:02:30.399 --> 00:02:32.440
So what was I able to do with the animation?

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:37.039
I was able to hold the tension in the story while I was bringing you along.

00:02:37.039 --> 00:02:41.639
And I was able to add a third variable to my story, which is not usually visible in

00:02:41.639 --> 00:02:42.639
a 2D plot.

00:02:42.639 --> 00:02:45.720
The third variable here was element of time.

00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:47.279
It was a season versus count.

00:02:47.279 --> 00:02:48.279
That's all it was.

00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:52.279
And I added that element of time where you saw episode by episode.

00:02:52.279 --> 00:02:54.720
That's what it allowed me to do.

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:56.279
Now let's come to the meat of it.

00:02:56.279 --> 00:02:57.279
How do you do it?

00:02:57.279 --> 00:03:02.199
This is where I'm going to talk about Plotly package, where I'm just going to talk about

00:03:02.199 --> 00:03:03.679
a very simple bar plot.

00:03:03.679 --> 00:03:07.520
I'm not going to go into how do you prettify the bar plot, because I just want to talk

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:11.259
about the basic code structure of animating something.

00:03:11.259 --> 00:03:12.679
So this is your simple bar plot.

00:03:12.679 --> 00:03:14.160
You've got a data set.

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:19.380
On Plotly, you use a Plotly function, give it the x and y variable, and simply call add

00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:20.380
bars function.

00:03:20.380 --> 00:03:24.679
It looks kind of pretty similar to ggplot if you're used to that.

00:03:24.679 --> 00:03:31.880
All you need to do to this to make it animated is give it a frame component within your add

00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:32.880
bars.

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:37.559
And what that frame equal to episode tells it is that don't just reveal my bar plot as

00:03:37.559 --> 00:03:42.440
it is, but build it frame by frame when I click on the play button.

00:03:42.679 --> 00:03:45.720
That's all that's needed to animate your bar plot.

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:49.960
You can also tell it how long to stay on a frame and how quick the transition to the

00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:52.800
next frame should be.

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:53.800
That's it.

00:03:53.800 --> 00:03:57.779
Now that we've talked about animation, let's move on to interactivity.

00:03:57.779 --> 00:04:01.740
And this is where we're going to get a little bit technical, because we might bring up some

00:04:01.740 --> 00:04:04.520
statistic concepts, but I'll hold your hand through it.

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:06.600
We're going to talk about Fscore.

00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:10.600
And some of you stat nerds might already know this, but let's talk about it anyway.

00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:16.959
An episode's Fscore is how many times Roy Kent drops the F bomb divided by the total

00:04:16.959 --> 00:04:18.920
number of F bombs in that episode.

00:04:18.920 --> 00:04:26.079
Or in other words, what's Roy Kent's contribution to that total episode's F bombs?

00:04:26.079 --> 00:04:28.079
Now I have another question for you.

00:04:28.079 --> 00:04:32.839
Which season do you think has the highest number of episodes where Roy Kent's contribution

00:04:32.839 --> 00:04:37.220
was greater than 50% or his Fscore was greater than 50%?

00:04:37.220 --> 00:04:39.059
And I have another hint for you.

00:04:39.059 --> 00:04:43.260
So this is the total count that we saw from the previous animation plot.

00:04:43.260 --> 00:04:46.040
So which season do you think is the answer?

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:49.859
Season one, two, three.

00:04:49.859 --> 00:04:56.100
Looks like you all are learning from the last quiz.

00:04:56.100 --> 00:04:57.700
So I'm just going to reveal the answer.

00:04:57.700 --> 00:04:59.940
No animation here.

00:04:59.940 --> 00:05:04.720
So this is how I could display the bar plot where every single episode, and there could

00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:09.299
be multiple more seasons, could be plotted in a single bar plot.

00:05:09.299 --> 00:05:13.100
And you could hover over it, look at the episode and the season that it's from, and look at

00:05:13.100 --> 00:05:14.100
the Fscore count.

00:05:14.100 --> 00:05:19.380
Or I could just add a simple thing to make it easier to visualize, where let's just look

00:05:19.380 --> 00:05:20.640
at season one.

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:25.220
So it has two episodes where the Fscore is greater than 50%.

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:30.380
Season three has got three episodes with greater than 50%.

00:05:30.380 --> 00:05:36.239
And season two, one, two, three, four episodes with greater than 50% Fscore.

00:05:36.239 --> 00:05:39.320
So season two, this time we all are the winners.

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:41.880
Now what was I able to do through interactivity?

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:45.339
I was able to turn my Viz into a dashboard-style report.

00:05:45.339 --> 00:05:49.079
And I know a lot of us have been asking, can that be a dashboard?

00:05:49.079 --> 00:05:51.880
So this is a great answer for that.

00:05:51.880 --> 00:05:55.899
And you were able to make your visualization more accessible by adding filtering.

00:05:55.899 --> 00:06:00.299
You could also add filters like scroll bars, where you just see the Fscore within a certain

00:06:00.299 --> 00:06:02.619
range.

00:06:02.619 --> 00:06:04.859
Now the meat of it, the code structure.

00:06:04.859 --> 00:06:08.700
I'm not going to dive again into the simple bar plot code structure, but a very quick

00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:10.540
recap of what that looks like.

00:06:10.540 --> 00:06:13.739
I am now going to introduce a package, Crosstalk.

00:06:13.739 --> 00:06:17.019
Now Crosstalk is exactly what the package name says.

00:06:17.019 --> 00:06:21.700
It allows you to talk between the checkbox and between the plot.

00:06:21.700 --> 00:06:26.059
So the first thing you do when you're using a Crosstalk package is create a shared data

00:06:26.059 --> 00:06:29.179
object that would be shared between those two components.

00:06:29.179 --> 00:06:30.299
How do you do that?

00:06:30.299 --> 00:06:34.119
So we created the bar plot on a data set.

00:06:34.119 --> 00:06:39.140
Instead of doing that, we will create a shared data object from that data set using Crosstalk's

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:40.839
shared data function.

00:06:40.839 --> 00:06:45.779
Now once you've created the shared data object, all you do is create the same bar plot that

00:06:45.779 --> 00:06:46.899
you had created.

00:06:46.899 --> 00:06:51.339
But instead of using data set, you just use this shared data object.

00:06:51.339 --> 00:06:53.100
Now what's the other thing you need?

00:06:53.100 --> 00:06:55.619
You need a checkbox.

00:06:55.619 --> 00:07:01.260
So Crosstalk has a filter checkbox function where you can create a checkbox component.

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:02.940
You give it a unique ID.

00:07:02.940 --> 00:07:05.399
You give it a label, which is a heading you see.

00:07:05.399 --> 00:07:10.059
You give it the shared data saying that use this shared data object, not any data set.

00:07:10.059 --> 00:07:15.380
And then the grouping equal to season just tells it, okay, what am I highlighting?

00:07:15.540 --> 00:07:22.019
You just place the checkbox and the plot side by side using the BS calls function, and that's

00:07:22.019 --> 00:07:23.019
it.

00:07:23.019 --> 00:07:28.459
You have an interactive plot right within your Quarto presentation or Quarto HTML, any

00:07:28.459 --> 00:07:33.380
type of HTML like your website or document.

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:34.720
Now let's talk about linking.

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:41.140
It's another type of interactivity, and a lot of you might know of it as brushing.

00:07:41.140 --> 00:07:43.260
So I have another question, but we're not going to raise hands.

00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:45.420
Don't worry this time.

00:07:45.420 --> 00:07:49.700
At some point throughout the seasons, Roy can start dating their PR manager Kaylee,

00:07:49.700 --> 00:07:50.700
pictured here.

00:07:50.700 --> 00:07:54.299
And at some point, he starts coaching the team.

00:07:54.299 --> 00:07:58.140
So I wanted to find out whether when he was dating, did he mellow down and the average

00:07:58.140 --> 00:08:02.299
F score go down maybe, or when he was coaching, did it go up?

00:08:02.299 --> 00:08:07.500
Well, I'm sure Ted Lazo fans must have started guessing the answer here, but I'm going to

00:08:07.500 --> 00:08:08.980
reveal it right away.

00:08:08.980 --> 00:08:10.779
So here's the answer.

00:08:10.779 --> 00:08:15.739
So when he was only dating, the average F score was 43% through those episodes.

00:08:15.739 --> 00:08:17.820
When he was only coaching, it was 39%.

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:22.540
But when he was dating and coaching, the average F score went up to 45%.

00:08:22.540 --> 00:08:23.899
Now this is fine.

00:08:23.899 --> 00:08:25.700
I asked a question.

00:08:25.700 --> 00:08:27.339
I answered the question.

00:08:27.339 --> 00:08:28.660
Nothing wrong with it.

00:08:28.660 --> 00:08:33.059
But as Roy Kent said, don't you dare settle for a fine.

00:08:33.059 --> 00:08:37.979
And I'm wearing that T-shirt as well because I'm channeling my Roy Kent energy.

00:08:37.979 --> 00:08:42.859
So let's add additional insights to this by linking it to another plot.

00:08:42.859 --> 00:08:46.619
So on the left-hand side of the plot we just saw, and on the right-hand side, I have the

00:08:46.619 --> 00:08:50.559
F count of every single episode and every single season.

00:08:50.559 --> 00:08:55.059
So let's say I wanted to see where he was dating only what are those episodes.

00:08:55.059 --> 00:08:57.179
So I'm able to highlight that real quick.

00:08:57.179 --> 00:09:01.020
Now let's say I wanted to see the episodes where he was only coaching.

00:09:01.020 --> 00:09:02.940
I'm able to highlight that as well.

00:09:02.940 --> 00:09:08.500
But let's say I want to know that when he was dating and coaching, what are the episodes

00:09:08.500 --> 00:09:13.859
that drove the F score to higher.

00:09:13.859 --> 00:09:15.619
So you can hover over this.

00:09:15.619 --> 00:09:19.900
Look at the episodes that are highlighted and see what were the F scores that were driving

00:09:19.900 --> 00:09:20.900
it up.

00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:23.700
Was it because Roy Kent dropped F bomb too many times?

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:27.340
Or was it because the episodes F count was just low in general?

00:09:27.340 --> 00:09:29.859
So you can drive more insights like this.

00:09:29.859 --> 00:09:31.299
Now what was I able to do?

00:09:31.299 --> 00:09:36.299
I was able to add layers to the story that I had started with, and I'm able to give my

00:09:36.299 --> 00:09:43.099
stakeholders more control to arrive at more insights than what they started with.

00:09:43.099 --> 00:09:46.619
Now the code, the structure of how do you create this linking?

00:09:46.619 --> 00:09:50.900
So again, we're going to start with the crosstalk package to create a shared data object between

00:09:50.900 --> 00:09:52.460
the two plots.

00:09:52.460 --> 00:09:54.500
So you've got the shared data object created.

00:09:54.500 --> 00:09:59.739
The only difference this time is the key that says, okay, dating or coaching flag.

00:09:59.739 --> 00:10:05.099
So if I select on anything, any episode that has dating and coaching flag as yes, highlight

00:10:05.099 --> 00:10:07.460
all the episodes simultaneously.

00:10:07.460 --> 00:10:10.179
That's what this key tells you to do.

00:10:10.179 --> 00:10:13.760
Now you'll just create the simple plotly plot that we had talked about.

00:10:13.760 --> 00:10:19.460
So this first plot is where I'm plotting for the average F score through episodes.

00:10:19.460 --> 00:10:25.140
And the second plot where I'm just plotting the F count versus each episode.

00:10:25.140 --> 00:10:29.719
And now you just place them side by side using the subplot command.

00:10:29.719 --> 00:10:30.719
That's it.

00:10:30.719 --> 00:10:35.039
You've got a linked plot, which one thing highlights and the other thing is highlighted

00:10:35.039 --> 00:10:36.119
by it.

00:10:36.119 --> 00:10:39.479
You can also give it how do you want the highlighting to work.

00:10:39.479 --> 00:10:43.640
So plotly has this very neat function called highlight where you can say persistent equal

00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:49.119
to true means if I highlight something, keep the previous highlight on still.

00:10:49.119 --> 00:10:51.840
On and off just means if I double click, turn it off.

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:54.039
If I click once, turn it on.

00:10:54.039 --> 00:10:58.320
And the dynamic equal to true means did you see that color bar where I can click on the

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:01.359
color and choose what color I want to do highlighting with?

00:11:01.359 --> 00:11:04.119
That's your dynamic equal to true.

00:11:04.119 --> 00:11:09.320
Now that you have all of these amazing tools for animation, interactivity, linking, let's

00:11:09.320 --> 00:11:11.719
combine all of it in one plot.

00:11:11.719 --> 00:11:15.080
In other words, don't do that unless needed.

00:11:15.080 --> 00:11:17.179
So I'm going to still show an example.

00:11:17.179 --> 00:11:22.960
So here I wanted to animate F count and F scores side by side and see if the trends

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:25.200
over seasons is similar.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:27.960
So I can add animation season over season.

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:34.719
I also wanted to give the stakeholders ability to click on a season and just dive into it.

00:11:34.719 --> 00:11:38.840
And I wanted to see, okay, if an episode has a high F count, does it mean they have a high

00:11:38.840 --> 00:11:41.280
F score, et cetera.

00:11:41.280 --> 00:11:47.039
So there's so much happening here that it gets a bit chaotic when you use too many tools

00:11:47.039 --> 00:11:48.440
in one place.

00:11:48.440 --> 00:11:53.640
So if you were planning to make everything animated and interactive, stop.

00:11:53.640 --> 00:11:58.640
Try to think about how it moves your story forward and how you can use it better.

00:11:58.640 --> 00:12:03.599
And if you're using it in a better way where it moves your story forward, right within

00:12:03.599 --> 00:12:07.080
Quarto you're able to add tension to your story.

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:11.200
You're able to add a third variable to an otherwise 2D plot.

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:17.479
You can turn some simple visualizations into a dashboard style and make it more accessible.

00:12:17.479 --> 00:12:22.239
You can add layers to your story and finally give your stakeholders more control by putting

00:12:22.239 --> 00:12:24.559
them in the driver's seat.

00:12:24.559 --> 00:12:29.000
Now some of the resources I wanted to share was there's a GitHub repo for this presentation

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:34.119
where you can look at the code I used to generate, but there's also a package where you can download

00:12:34.119 --> 00:12:39.599
the data of F counts dropped by Roykin and the entire episode.

00:12:39.599 --> 00:12:41.880
So feel free to go nuts.

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:46.239
And finally, I hope this makes you believe that you can easily get started with it.

00:12:46.239 --> 00:12:47.239
And that's it.

00:12:47.239 --> 00:12:48.239
Thank you.

00:12:48.239 --> 00:12:59.479
Thank you.

00:12:59.479 --> 00:13:01.799
Thank you.

00:13:01.799 --> 00:13:03.400
We have one question for you.

00:13:03.400 --> 00:13:06.000
I guess not directly a Quarto question.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:10.039
So the question is can you put these animations and crosstalk into Shiny apps?

00:13:10.039 --> 00:13:11.039
Yes.

00:13:11.039 --> 00:13:13.359
Yes, you can.

00:13:13.359 --> 00:13:14.719
I will make it a Quarto question.

00:13:14.719 --> 00:13:20.599
You can also put Shiny in Quarto, which there's some blogs on my website linked at the bottom

00:13:20.599 --> 00:13:21.719
that you can check out.

00:13:21.719 --> 00:13:22.840
There's a blog about that as well.

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:27.640
But yes, plotly and crosstalk is something you can easily use within Shiny as well.

00:13:27.640 --> 00:13:28.640
Thank you.

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:30.080
And let's thank all the speakers of this session.

